The PredatAR 5.56 is designed for those who are searching for a lightweight, ultra-reliable and accurate 5.56 mm NATO rifle for home-defense, competition-shooting or hunting. The PredatAR takes the highly accurate OBR 5.56 “Lite” design, and lightens it in every possible way with the least possible impact to the accuracy that the standard OBR is known for. By contouring the barrel, skeletonizing the handguard, lowering and simplifying the upper rail, and using a low-profile gas block, we were able to reduce roughly 2 pounds from the standard OBR 5.56 rifle.

The barrels are lightweight-profiled with rifling in a 1/8 twist rate. All barrels are threaded in ½ x 28, with an A2 flash hider attached* (other muzzle devices can be added at an additional cost).

The handguards on the PredatAR extend out 14.75”, to suit a larger range of shooting styles. The zero-MOA upper rail provides plenty of room for weapon-mounted night-vision day/night combinations. Both the upper and lower are CNC-machined from billet aluminum for the optimum fit and consistency. Even though we lightened certain features, there is still additional material in strategic areas to achieve maximum accuracy. Each rifle ships with one, 3” long, MIL-STD-1913 detachable rail section.

Both models come with a 6-position LaRue RAT Stock and LaRue medium A-PEG™ Grip. The Bolt Carriers are hand-polished hard-chrome with staked carrier keys, with Texas-Spec Bolt assemblies.

No LaRue firearm can leave the facility unless it obtains accuracy of less-than 1 MOA (1.047”) at 100 Yards. Each firearm ships with a copy of a 3-round group obtained from that actual firearm. While we guarantee the rifle is capable of sub-MOA accuracy, we can not guarantee the end-user will be able to shoot sub-MOA…since we have no control over shooting proficiency, familiarity with the system, ammunition choice, environmental factors, etc. LaRue firearms are precision instruments that require discipline, training, proper ammunition and maintenance to yield the best results.

title: For Sale/Trade:  H&k 91 / PTR 91 / CETME  .308 Battle Rifle with (50) 20 rd Mags
postcontent: Made from real machine gun parts imported with the last supply of former military CETME parts.  When the manufacturer made the trigger pack into a semiautomatic, they just cut off the full auto sear section that pinned to the gun and welded a shelf/stop inside it. The full auto disconnect  just floats freely inside the trigger pack from wear it was cUT off. H&K bought the patent and took over CETME rifles.  There will only be limited supply of these original parts guns, as all the last supply has already been bought by Century Arms.  PTR Industries "PTR-91" bought all of H&K equipment overseas and brought it to the USA to make H&K clones with the old equipment. Century Arms has teamed up with PTR Industries and are using PTR made receivers and barrels along with all original military surplus parts to make this H&K / CETME Clone the "C308".  This gun takes all G3 machine gun / H&K 91 magazines. This gun runs flawless as all parts are original and the new receiver & barrel are military spec from PTR. The rifle comes with "50" magazines that hold 20 rounds of .308/7.62 NATO. This is a beast of a set-up for anyone looking for a high capacity gun.

title: For Sale:  Federal High Velocity 9mm Ammo Made For Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
postcontent:
I have some Federal Hi-Shok 115 grain jacketed hollow point ammunition for sale. This lot is an overrun for the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and is loaded to +p pressure levels, even though the cases are not marked +p. You can expect around 1250 feet per second from a Glock 19 or other 4 inch barreled handgun.

Velocity is key to the 9mm round. This bullet, the Hi-Shok, is not bonded and fragments upon impact with soft tissue. This fragmentation creates many wound channels, while the core of the bullet penetrates well over 12 inches in ballistic gelatin. This is a perfect carry round, where overpenetration is a concern. If you are a CCW holder, you are financially responsible for the bullet you fire if it were to penetrate completely and strike another person.

The best thing about this bullet is the price. Most 9mm ball runs around $15 per box of 50 at the local retail stores. This box of 50 is $19, only $4 more. Overpressure hollow point ammo is usually expensive, but because this is a contract overrun, you can save.

I can't tell you much. In the late seventies I made maybe a half dozen similar pistols from CVA kits and sold them. Two of these I hand filed to octagon to round barrels. As I recall, I shortened the barrels and stocks on all of them. I never liked long pistols. I believe I reset the barrel lugs where the front lock bolt would secure the barrels. The nose cap is poured pewter. The inlayed rings in the barrel are brass. Not gold.The silver wire was from pure silver, and I still have some of it. Been a long time. As to value, I would not know what to say. These are all pre-1980, and all were percussion. I did not make the box that one is in. Thank you. That brings back fond memories.
